## STEP 1 — Log into YOUR OWN macOS account

On a shared Mac this is the most important step. Before you do anything else:

- Look at the top-right of the menu bar. If it shows the other person's name, click it and switch to YOUR name (or log out and back in).
- All the following steps happen while logged in as YOU. Your bot token, API keys, config, and chat history will live under your account (in `~/.openclaw`). The other person cannot see any of it unless they know your Mac password.

> ⚠️ **Do not use someone else's account.** If you install OpenClaw while logged in as your housemate (or as any account where OpenClaw is already set up for someone else), the installer may ask "wipe old data?" — answering yes would **permanently delete their setup**. Only install on a macOS account that is YOURS, and where OpenClaw has never been installed before.
>
> **How to check:** open Terminal and run:
>
> ```
> ls ~/.openclaw
> ```
>
> If the command says `No such file or directory`, you're on a clean account — safe to continue. If it lists files, OpenClaw is already set up on this account. Only continue if those files are yours; otherwise **switch accounts** before going further.

## STEP 2 — Open Terminal

On your Mac (while logged in as yourself):

- Press **Command + Space** (opens Spotlight search).
- Type: `Terminal`
- Press **Enter**.

![Opening Spotlight with Cmd+Space](images/21-terminal-spotlight.png)

A window with text will open. This is where you'll run the installer.

## STEP 3 — Unzip the toolkit and run the installer

You received a file called `{{zip_name}}` via message. Make sure the copy you use is inside your own user folder (for example, your Downloads folder while logged in as you — not the other person's).

1. In Finder, double-click the zip. macOS will unzip it into a folder.
2. Open the folder. Inside you'll see at least these files:

   ```
   install.sh
   install.command
   skills   (a sub-folder)
   ```

You can start the installer in one of two ways.

> **Not sure which to pick? Use Way A.** It never triggers the "unidentified developer" pop-up that may appear with Way B.

### Way A — drag-to-Terminal (RECOMMENDED, no pop-up warnings)

1. Make sure the Terminal window from STEP 2 is open.
2. Click in the Terminal window. Type the four characters `bash` then press the SPACE BAR once. Do NOT press Enter yet.
3. Drag the file `install.sh` from the Finder folder into the Terminal window. The file's full path will appear right after `bash `.
4. Now press **Enter**.

![Terminal with install.sh path dragged in](images/22-installer-drag-path.png)

### Way B — double-click (simpler, but the first run triggers a macOS pop-up you have to click through)

1. In Finder, double-click `install.command`.
2. The first time you do this, macOS will almost certainly show:

   > "install.command cannot be opened because it is from an unidentified developer."

   This is NORMAL — the file is safe, it just isn't signed by Apple. To get past it:

   a. Close the pop-up.
   b. Back in Finder, right-click (or Control-click) on `install.command`.
   c. Choose **Open** from the menu.
   d. Click **Open** in the confirmation dialog.

   macOS will remember your choice. Future runs open directly.

3. A new Terminal window will open and start the installer.

### When the installer asks for your keys

Either way, after a few seconds the installer will stop and ask two questions. Paste from your checklist:

- **Telegram bot token:** paste key **#1** → press **Enter**.
- **Anthropic API key:** paste key **#2** → press **Enter**.

![Installer prompting for Telegram bot token and Anthropic API key](images/23-installer-key-prompts.png)

If the installer detects an existing OpenClaw install on this account, it will ask:

> Wipe old data first? (y/N)

> ⚠️ **Press Enter** (which means "No") unless you are 100% sure the existing install is **yours** and you want to start over. Typing `y` here permanently deletes the bot pairing, saved settings, and chat history of whoever set up this account. On a shared Mac, if you are not sure whose install it is — **stop, press Enter, and check with your housemate first.**

Near the end of the installer, watch for a line like this:

```
[OK] gateway healthy on 127.0.0.1:18790
```

The number after the colon is YOUR slot. The first person to install on the Mac usually gets 18789, the second person 18790, and so on. You don't need to type this number anywhere — just know it's yours. The installer picks a free one automatically.

Wait for it to finish. When it's done you'll see a success message. At the very end, a browser tab will open automatically — that's your **OpenClaw Control UI (dashboard)**. Don't close it; you'll use it in the next step.

## STEP 4 — Find your OpenClaw dashboard

The installer opened a browser tab titled **OpenClaw**. Switch to that tab now — it should still be open from Step 3. You don't need to do anything in it yet; just leave it open so you can glance at it while you set up the bot.

Each person on this Mac has their own dashboard, running on their own slot — you won't see your housemate's data.

![OpenClaw Control UI opened in browser](images/24-dashboard-opened.png)

If the tab isn't there — you closed it, or the installer couldn't open it — go back to Terminal and run:

⌨️ **Paste this into Terminal and press Enter:**

```
openclaw dashboard
```

That will reopen the dashboard.

## STEP 5 — Say hi to your bot

Open Telegram. In the search bar, type the bot username YOU chose with BotFather, and tap your bot. Make sure it's **YOURS**, not your housemate's. First time opening the chat, Telegram shows a big **Start** button — tap it.

![Empty Telegram chat with the bot — Start button](images/25-telegram-bot-start.png)

📲 **Copy this and send it to your bot** (or just tap **Start** — it sends the same command):

```
/start
```

The bot will reply with something like this:

```
OpenClaw: access not configured.
Your Telegram user id: 1048152213
Pairing code: 6P25BBXP

Ask the bot owner to approve with:
openclaw pairing approve telegram 6P25BBXP
```

![Bot's pairing-request reply](images/26-telegram-pairing-message.png)

Don't worry — this is expected. The bot is asking you to prove you're the owner. The next step approves it.

## STEP 6 — Approve yourself in Terminal

Look at the bot's reply above — find the **Pairing code** line (an 8-character code). Copy that code.

Go back to your Terminal window (the same one from Step 3, still logged in as you — this writes to YOUR user folder).

⌨️ **Paste this into Terminal and press Enter** (replace `XXXXXXXX` with your actual pairing code):

```
openclaw pairing approve telegram XXXXXXXX
```

![Terminal showing successful pairing approval](images/27-terminal-approval-success.png)

Terminal prints a success confirmation. Now send your bot any message — e.g. "hello" — and it will reply like a real assistant. You're paired.

## STEP 7 — Set up the content monitor

This step takes 5–10 minutes. The bot will ask **7 questions** one at a time. Have these ready before you start:

- **List of competitor websites** to monitor — or just use the default 56 pre-configured sites.
- **Facebook + X (Twitter) login** — the bot opens a browser and you log in manually. Skip either if you want to set it up later.
- **Sample post** showing your writing style (a post you've written, 100–500 words) — or skip to use a professional default.
- **Your website domain** (e.g. `www.mysite.com`) — used for internal link suggestions. Skip if you don't have one yet.
- **Preferred time + timezone** for the daily pipeline. Default is 7:00 AM Asia/Saigon.
- **Keys #3, #4, #5** from your checklist (Firecrawl, Google AI, Brave).

When you're ready, send this to your bot:

📲 **Copy this and send it to your bot:**

```
/content-monitor setup
```

![Telegram with /content-monitor setup sent](images/28-telegram-setup-sent.png)

The bot replies with the 7-step overview and starts asking one question at a time.

### Question 1 of 7 — Competitor websites

The bot asks what sites you want to monitor.

📲 **To use the default 56 sites, send:**

```
use defaults
```

Or paste your own list — one URL per line, like this:

```
https://www.example-competitor-1.com
https://www.example-competitor-2.com
```

![Setup Q1 — competitor website list](images/29-setup-q1-websites.png)

The bot will then ask, for each URL, whether it's **personal-injury**, **mortgage**, or **other**.

### Question 2 of 7 — Facebook + X login

The bot opens a browser window and asks you to log into Facebook first — log in manually with **your own** account (not your housemate's).

![Facebook login page opened by the bot](images/30-facebook-login.png)

Then the bot opens an X (Twitter) tab — log in there too, or skip.

![X (Twitter) login page opened by the bot](images/31-x-login.png)

📲 **When you've finished logging in, send:**

```
done
```

The bot confirms which account it sees and moves on.

![Social login confirmed by the bot](images/32-setup-social-confirmed.png)

📲 **Or to skip a platform (and set it up later):**

```
skip
```

### Question 3 of 7 — Writing style sample

The bot asks for a sample of your writing so it can match your tone.

📲 **To skip and use a default professional style, send:**

```
skip
```

Or paste a post you've written before (any length — 100–500 words works best). Or paste a URL to a page that has your writing, and the bot will read it.

### Question 4 of 7 — Weekly content themes

The bot shows you a 7-day theme schedule (Monday = "Know Your Rights", Tuesday = "HEI Education", etc.).

📲 **To keep the defaults, send:**

```
keep defaults
```

Or say `customize` and the bot will walk you through each day one at a time.

### Question 5 of 7 — API keys

The bot asks for 3 keys, one at a time. You already have all three from the checklist in the "BEFORE YOU START" section — **paste all three, don't skip any**.

- **Firecrawl API key:** paste key **#3**.
- **Google AI API key:** paste key **#4**.

![Setup Q5 — Firecrawl and Google AI key prompts](images/33-setup-q5-api-keys.png)

- **Brave Search API key:** paste key **#5**.

![Setup Q5 — Brave Search key prompt](images/34-setup-q5-brave.png)

### Question 6 of 7 — Your website domain

📲 **Paste your domain (no `https://` needed), like:**

```
www.mysite.com
```

📲 **Or skip if you don't have one yet:**

```
skip
```

### Question 7 of 7 — Daily schedule

The bot asks what time to run the daily content pipeline.

📲 **For the default (7:00 AM Asia/Saigon), send:**

```
default
```

Or enter your own time, like `7:00 AM` or `08:30`. The bot will then ask for your timezone — send `default` for Asia/Saigon, or enter one like `America/Los_Angeles` or `Europe/London`.

![Setup Q7 — daily schedule confirmed, first-time crawl starting](images/35-setup-q7-schedule.png)

### After all 7 questions

The bot automatically sets up the workspace folders (under YOUR user account only), does a first-time crawl of all competitor sites (takes a few minutes), and sends you a summary table showing what's configured. You're done — the daily pipeline will now run on the schedule you picked, for you alone.

![Setup complete — configuration summary](images/36-setup-complete-summary.png)

## STEP 8 — Test that it works

📲 **Copy this and send it to your bot:**

```
run content pipeline
```

The bot runs the pipeline once and reports today's content candidates — usually two posts drawn from the day's theme.

![Pipeline — today's content candidates](images/37-pipeline-candidates.png)

Reply with `1`, `2`, or `both` to pick which candidate the bot should turn into a full post.

![Pipeline — pick which post to use](images/38-pipeline-post-selection.png)

The bot writes the full post, pastes it back, and asks whether to approve. Send `approve` (or `edit [instructions]`, `regenerate image`, or `skip`).

![Pipeline — approve the draft](images/39-pipeline-approve.png)

Once approved, the bot posts to Facebook (and X if you're logged in).

![Published Facebook post](images/40-facebook-posted.png)

Finally the bot prints a one-line summary — which platforms it posted to and which it skipped. Done! 🎉

![Pipeline summary — platform post status](images/41-pipeline-summary.png)

If the other person hasn't installed yet, they can now log out, let them log in, and repeat from STEP 1 with their own zip, their own bot, and their own 5 keys.

## Can we install at the same time?

Technically yes — but it's cleaner if one person finishes first. The installer checks which slots are currently in use, so if two installers run at the exact same moment, they might both see the same slot as free and both try to use it. If that happens, whoever runs second will see their bot fail to respond. Running the installer once more fixes it.

## Troubleshooting

**"Permission denied" when running install.sh**

- Use Way A from STEP 3: open Terminal, type `bash` and a space, then drag `install.sh` into Terminal, then press Enter.
- This works even if the file lost its permission to run during unzip.

**install.command won't open — "unidentified developer" pop-up**

- Right-click (or Control-click) on `install.command` in Finder.
- Choose **Open**, then click **Open** in the confirmation dialog.
- macOS will remember your choice after that.

**Unzipping didn't create a folder**

- Try double-clicking the zip again in Finder — macOS's built-in Archive Utility is the most reliable. Avoid third-party unzip apps.

**The browser tab with the dashboard didn't open**

- Go to Terminal and run:

  ⌨️ **Paste this into Terminal and press Enter:**

  ```
  openclaw dashboard
  ```

**I don't want the dashboard to auto-open on install**

- Re-run the installer with this in front:

  ⌨️ **Paste this into Terminal and press Enter** (replace the path with your actual install.sh path):

  ```
  OPENCLAW_NO_DASHBOARD=1 bash /path/to/install.sh
  ```

**The bot doesn't reply**

- Make sure you completed STEP 6 (approval).
- Check that you're messaging the RIGHT bot (the one YOU made with BotFather, not your housemate's).

**"invalid Telegram bot token format"**

- The token should look like `123456789:AA...` (a number, a colon, then letters/numbers).
- Re-copy it from BotFather and try again.

**"invalid Anthropic API key"**

- The key must start with `sk-ant-`.
- Re-copy it from [platform.claude.com](https://platform.claude.com/settings/workspaces/default/keys) and try again.

**"Image generation hit an issue — billing needs to be enabled"**

- Google AI image generation requires a billing account. Go to [aistudio.google.com/billing](https://aistudio.google.com/billing) and add a payment method for your project, then ask the bot to `regenerate image`.

**"skills/ not found next to install.sh"**

- The zip was unzipped incompletely or the `skills` folder was moved.
- Re-unzip the original zip file and run the installer from inside the fresh folder (inside your own user folder).

**"no free port in 18789-18798"**

- All ten reserved slots are taken. This usually means old OpenClaw daemons from past installs are still running in the background. Ask whoever set up the Mac to investigate, or run this in Terminal to see what's holding them:

  ⌨️ **Paste this into Terminal and press Enter:**

  ```
  lsof -iTCP:18789-18798 -sTCP:LISTEN
  ```

**Your bot replies with someone else's messages**

- You're probably pointing at a bot that's already paired with another person's install. Open BotFather, create a NEW bot, and re-run the installer — it will ask for the new bot token.

**Bot stopped replying after the other person installed**

- Your own gateway service may have lost its slot. Re-run `install.sh` from inside your toolkit folder. Answer **N** (or press Enter) when asked whether to wipe existing data — the installer will keep your config and just refresh the gateway service on a fresh free slot.

**Something else**

- Copy the error message and ask for help.

## 📖 What you can say to your bot

A quick reference of messages the bot understands. Send any of these in Telegram like a normal chat message.

### General

| Say this               | What happens                                       |
|------------------------|----------------------------------------------------|
| `/start` or `hi`       | Greets the bot. First time, triggers pairing.      |
| any free-text message  | Regular AI-assistant reply.                        |

### Content monitor

| Say this                   | What happens                                         |
|----------------------------|------------------------------------------------------|
| `/content-monitor setup`   | Starts guided first-time setup.                      |
| `setup content monitor`    | Same as above, plain-English version.                |
| `run content pipeline`     | Runs the pipeline once so you can verify it works.   |
| `approve`                  | Approves the most recent draft the bot showed you.   |
| `what's new today?`        | Asks the monitor for today's topic suggestions.      |

Add more bot skills later? Come back and check this section.

## Keeping things tidy

Nothing crosses between accounts. Each person's bot token, API keys, config, and chat history live under their own macOS account (in `~/.openclaw`). You cannot see each other's data unless someone shares their password — keep it that way.

## Keep these safe

Your 5 keys (Telegram bot token, Anthropic, Firecrawl, Google AI, Brave) are like passwords. Don't share them publicly — screenshots, chats, emails, or code repositories. Don't share them with the other person on the Mac either — they have their own. If one leaks, regenerate it on the provider's dashboard:

- Telegram bot token → [BotFather](https://t.me/BotFather)
- Anthropic → [platform.claude.com/settings/workspaces/default/keys](https://platform.claude.com/settings/workspaces/default/keys)
- Firecrawl → [firecrawl.dev](https://www.firecrawl.dev/)
- Google AI → [aistudio.google.com/api-keys](https://aistudio.google.com/api-keys)
- Brave Search → [api-dashboard.search.brave.com/app/keys](https://api-dashboard.search.brave.com/app/keys)
